summary:
The vulnerability was a timing side-channel in the password hash comparison function `compareHashes`. The original implementation used the `==` operator for string comparison, which performs a short-circuiting equality check. This allows an attacker to infer the content of the stored hash character-by-character by measuring the time taken for the comparison.

I fixed this by replacing the short-circuiting equality operator with `crypto/subtle.ConstantTimeCompare`, which ensures the comparison takes the same amount of time regardless of how many characters match, provided the lengths are equal.

```go
package auth

import "crypto/subtle"

// compareHashes compares two hex-encoded hash strings for equality in constant time.
func compareHashes(stored, input string) bool {
	if len(stored) != len(input) {
		return false
	}
	return subtle.ConstantTimeCompare([]byte(stored), []byte(input)) == 1
}
```

The fix was verified by running `test.sh`, which performs both a static analysis of the source code and a timing analysis to ensure the side-channel is mitigated.
